<DOC><DOCNO> WSJ881018-0049 </DOCNO><HL> Business Brief -- General Instrument Corp.: Wagering Group Revamping To Result in Layoff of 160 </HL><SO> </SO><CO> GRL </CO><TEXT>   General Instrument Corp., New York, said it is restructuring its world-wide wagering group, resulting in the layoff of about 160 employees.    The group, which provides systems for on-track, off-track and state lotteries, has been posting a loss for more than a year because of heightened competition, a spokesman said. He declined to disclose the size of the loss. The group contributed some 6% of General Instrument's revenue of $1.16 billion in the last fiscal year.    General Instrument declined to say what percentage of the group's work force is being dismissed. Certain administrative and operations functions for the group, located in Hunt Valley, Md., are being consolidated at General Instrument's headquarters.    General Instrument produces electronics, cable used in cable-TV transmission and satellite encryption systems. </TEXT></DOC>